                <head>2. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In his memoir, <hi rend="italic">The Right Hand of Power</hi>, pages 513–514,
                        <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis Johnson</persName>, who stepped down
                    as Ambassador to Japan in mid-January 1969 to become Under Secretary of State
                    for Political Affairs under President Nixon, recalled meeting <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry Kissinger</persName> at the Hotel Pierre in New York
                    City on the evening of January 5, 1969. Although the meeting lasted only about
                    15 minutes, “that was long enough for me to see that some rough roads lay ahead.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName> outlined his thoughts for
                    wiping out the <gloss target="#t_SIG1">SIG</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_IRG1"
                        >IRG</gloss> interdepartmental system General <persName corresp="#p_TMD1"
                        >Taylor</persName> and I had developed in 1966 that gave State broad
                    responsibility for directing the interdepartmental work of the government in
                    foreign affairs. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName> intended to
                    establish a system centered on the National Security Council staff with himself
                    as head. I had only two minutes to expostulate <pb facs="0042" n="11"
                        xml:id="pg_11"/> with <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName>. As I was
                    going down the elevator to get a cab to the airport, I tried to brief <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_REL1"
                        >Richardson</persName> on the important bureaucratic theology involved in
                    the <gloss target="#t_SIG1">SIG</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_IRG1">IRG</gloss> as
                    far as State was concerned—an area with which, of course, they were entirely
                    unfamiliar. I brooded about this on my flight back, and as soon as I arrived in
                    Tokyo I sent a long back channel message to <persName corresp="#p_REL1"
                        >Richardson</persName> trying to explicate the issues involved and urging
                    that he and the Secretary mount the ramparts before January 20 against the
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>/<gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> takeover of State’s interdepartmental functions.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>’s back channel message to <persName
                        corresp="#p_REL1">Richardson</persName> has not been found. The
                    establishment of the <gloss target="#t_SIG1">SIG</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_IRG1"
                        >IRG</gloss> system in 1966 and its operation through the close of 1968 are
                    documented in <ref target="frus1964-68v33">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1964–1968, volume XXXIII,
                        Organization and Management of U.S. Foreign Policy; United Nations</ref>.
                    For <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>’s role in establishing the
                    system, see <ref target="frus1964-68v33#d48">Document 48</ref>.</p>
